The COVID-19 outbreak, which started in late 2019, has presented difficulties for worldwide public health systems. A key challenge throughout this current crisis has been the crazy nature of infection rates, which can result in unexpected spikes in cases. As countries persist in encountering waves of infections, anticipating these outbreaks in advance to facilitate effective responses is essential. The capability to predict when and where these spikes may happen would assist healthcare officials in distributing resources more effectively, initiating public health measures ahead of time, and reducing the social and economic impacts linked to unexpected outbreaks.

This study aimed to utilize predictive analytics methods to estimate the probability of COVID-19 case increases in certain areas in the coming 7 to 14 days. This research aimed to create a model that could detect early warning signals of surges by using data on essential public health indicators, including new confirmed cases, testing rates, vaccination rates, and government policy responses. The results of this project may enhance decision-making and improve pandemic response
